content: It's a bit misleading. When you click on certain vessels to get more info, it will pop up with the "position received via satellite" info. You then have to pay for the satellite service. replyContent:
Hi Renier,  I am sorry for the confusion.
We haven't removed any functionality. In fact, we added a low-budget feature where you can get SAT positions and extra features for 1 vessel.

You can also reach out to us at customersupport@marinetraffic.com.

For years I enjoyed identifying ships on San Francisco Bay with the Port of San Francisco app which used your tracker. Then I would click on a boat and find out where it's from, what it's name is. When I found out that I could download the app it just expanded into a whole different Realm. My friend in Poland sent me a couple of photos that he shot of a cargo ship passing him on a relatively small waterway. It was the LONGVANN. Now I follow the LONGVANN and with Google maps I can get closer look at the ports and the clues of what the LONGVANN is transporting. I'd like to encourage everyone to use Google to explore the places where the ships that you follow go.You can touch a building, and if Google has taken a street view you can descend into another part of the world. If Google has toured around you can follow the blue line in the street and tour the ville. BON VOYAGE!!!

Thank you for your feedback and ideas!
We recently introduced the SAT1 add-on, for those who only want to track one vessel via satellite. Available on the website, under My Fleet - Fleet Settings.
For "vessels near me" just enable auto-tracking (under Settings) and then use the group button at the top menu.

For those saying information is wrong or missing:. This information is 
based only on the ship's AIS, so if the captain turns AIS off or does not 
update things like ETA, destination, or even position because you can turn 
off automatic position update, then the app will show that it isn't 
updated. Having AIS can be great, but it creates security issues, there are 
terrorists that could use this information to plan attacks. It's a good app 
for displaying the information it has, it's limited to the information 
available

Hi Jonathan!
A GPS compass is used in the autotracking feature, when we need to know the direction we are moving. This however does not provide any information of the device orientation which can be aquired only by the magnetic compass.

2nd review after a couple of days using this. I'm just a hobbyist using it to monitor my home port and so far it has done everything I have asked of it which is not surprising as once I visited the website I realised that really this is aimed towards the professional user (and has pricing options to match!) - guess I've just become cynical with some of the rubbish that abounds on Goggle Play....  So given thats the angle I'm coming from here are a couple of things / improvements I would like to see in the future.  It would be great if user generated off-line maps could be viewed so public domain charts or annotated charts could be used as the chart option is prohibitively expensive for a hobbyist. I am using wifi so I dont know whether this would be good for mobile users also rather than having to access the same data over and over..  It could do with a +/- zoom button option to ease 1 finger use.  The ship info "bubble"would be better related to ship icon rather than interface size.  The ports option would benefit from a basic frequency / channel list although I realise that for world wide coverage this is probably a whole new project in itself.  First Class!
